cql:
library PregnantwomenthathadHBsAgtesting version '6.0.001'

using QDM version '5.3'

valueset "ONC Administrative Sex": 'urn:oid:2.16.840.1.113762.1.4.1'
valueset "Race": 'urn:oid:2.16.840.1.114222.4.11.836'
valueset "Ethnicity": 'urn:oid:2.16.840.1.114222.4.11.837'
valueset "Payer": 'urn:oid:2.16.840.1.114222.4.11.3591'
valueset "Delivery - Diagnosis": 'urn:oid:2.16.840.1.113883.3.67.1.101.1.278'
valueset "Delivery - Procedure": 'urn:oid:2.16.840.1.113762.1.4.1078.5'
valueset "Female": 'urn:oid:2.16.840.1.113883.3.560.100.2'
valueset "HBsAg": 'urn:oid:2.16.840.1.113883.3.67.1.101.1.279'
valueset "Hepatitis B": 'urn:oid:2.16.840.1.113883.3.67.1.101.1.269'

parameter "Measurement Period" Interval<DateTime>

context Patient

define "SDE Ethnicity":
	["Patient Characteristic Ethnicity": "Ethnicity"]

define "SDE Payer":
	["Patient Characteristic Payer": "Payer"]

define "SDE Race":
	["Patient Characteristic Race": "Race"]

define "SDE Sex":
	["Patient Characteristic Sex": "ONC Administrative Sex"]

define "Most Recent Delivery":
	Last(["Procedure, Performed": "Delivery - Procedure"] DeliveryProcedure
			where DeliveryProcedure.relevantPeriod during "Measurement Period"
			sort by start of relevantPeriod
	)

define "Denominator Exceptions":
	exists ( ["Diagnosis": "Hepatitis B"] HepB
			with "Most Recent Delivery Overlaps Diagnosis" DeliveryOverlapsDiagnosis
				such that HepB.prevalencePeriod starts 365 days or less before start of DeliveryOverlapsDiagnosis.relevantPeriod
					or HepB.prevalencePeriod ends 365 days or less before start of DeliveryOverlapsDiagnosis.relevantPeriod
	)

define "Most Recent Delivery Overlaps Diagnosis":
	"Most Recent Delivery" MostRecentDelivery
		where exists ( ["Diagnosis": "Delivery - Diagnosis"] DeliveryDiagnosis
				where MostRecentDelivery.relevantPeriod overlaps DeliveryDiagnosis.prevalencePeriod
		)

define "Initial Population":
	"Most Recent Delivery Overlaps Diagnosis" is not null
		and AgeInYearsAt(start of "Measurement Period")>= 12
		and exists ( ["Patient Characteristic Sex": "Female"] )

define "Numerator":
	exists ( ["Laboratory Test, Performed": "HBsAg"] LabTest
			with "Most Recent Delivery Overlaps Diagnosis" DeliveryOverlapsDiagnosis
				such that LabTest.relevantPeriod starts 280 days or less before start of DeliveryOverlapsDiagnosis.relevantPeriod
	)

define "Denominator":
	"Initial Population"
description: This measure identifies pregnant women who had a HBsAg (hepatitis B) test during their pregnancy

measure_attributes.value: The U.S. Preventive Services Task Force (USPSTF) found good evidence that universal prenatal screening for hepatitis B virus (HBV) infection using hepatitis B surface antigen (HBsAg) substantially reduces prenatal transmission of HBV and the subsequent development of chronic HBV infection (USPSTF 2009). The current practice of vaccinating all infants against HBV infection and post-exposure prophylaxis with hepatitis B immune globulin administered at birth to infants of HBV-infected mothers substantially reduces the risk for acquiring HBV infection.
measure_attributes.name: Rationale

value_obj.value: The U.S. Preventive Services Task Force (USPSTF) found good evidence that universal prenatal screening for hepatitis B virus (HBV) infection using hepatitis B surface antigen (HBsAg) substantially reduces prenatal transmission of HBV and the subsequent development of chronic HBV infection (USPSTF 2009). The current practice of vaccinating all infants against HBV infection and post-exposure prophylaxis with hepatitis B immune globulin administered at birth to infants of HBV-infected mothers substantially reduces the risk for acquiring HBV infection.

measure_attributes.value: The U.S. Preventive Services Task Force (USPSTF) strongly recommends screening for hepatitis B virus (HBV) infection in pregnant women at their first prenatal visit (USPSTF 2009). This is a grade A* recommendation from the USPSTF. In addition, the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) recommend screening all pregnant women for HBV infection (ACOG 2007).
measure_attributes.name: Clinical Recommendation Statement

value_obj.value: The U.S. Preventive Services Task Force (USPSTF) strongly recommends screening for hepatitis B virus (HBV) infection in pregnant women at their first prenatal visit (USPSTF 2009). This is a grade A* recommendation from the USPSTF. In addition, the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) recommend screening all pregnant women for HBV infection (ACOG 2007).

measure_attributes.value: U.S. Preventive Services Task Force. Screening for Hepatitis B Virus Infection in Pregnancy: U.S.Preventive Services Task Force Reaffirmation Recommendation Statement. Ann Int Med 2009;150:869-73.
